Class TernaryHeap

IntroTernaryHeap
public class TernaryHeap extends Heap
Ternary Heap Sort which uses a ternary heap instead of a binary heap; that is, each element in the heap has three children. Ternary Heap Sort is somewhat more complicated to program, but it is potentially faster. Each step in the sift operation of a ternary heap requires three comparisons and one swap, whereas in a binary heap two comparisons and one swap are required. The ternary heap can do two steps in less time than the binary heap requires for three steps.
Since:
1.0

    • TernaryHeap

      public TernaryHeap()
      Ternary Heap Sort:
      Which uses a ternary heap instead of a binary heap; that is, each element in the heap has three children. Ternary Heap Sort is somewhat more complicated to program, but it is potentially faster. Each step in the sift operation of a ternary heap requires three comparisons and one swap, whereas in a binary heap two comparisons and one swap are required. The ternary heap can do two steps in less time than the binary heap requires for three steps.

      Example:
      1. Build a binary heap from the input array. This is done by starting with the last parent node in the array and repeatedly heapify the array to satisfy the heap property.
        • heapify is a process where the element at index i is compared with its children, and if necessary, swapped to maintain the heap property (max-heap or min-heap).
        • This process is performed for all parent nodes, starting from the last parent down to the root.
      2. Once the binary heap is constructed, repeatedly extract the maximum (or minimum) element from the heap and place it at the end of the array.
        • Swap the root element (which is the maximum or minimum element depending on whether it's a max-heap or min-heap) with the last element of the heap.
        • Reduce the size of the heap by one.
        • Perform heapify on the root to restore the heap property.
      3. Repeat step 2 until all elements have been extracted from the heap. The extracted elements will be in the reverse order for a max-heap (sorted in ascending order) or in the correct order for a min-heap (sorted in descending order).
      Note:
      Thus, because of the O(n log(n)) upper bound on heapsort's running time and constant upper bound on its auxiliary storage, embedded systems with real-time constraints or systems concerned with security often use heapsort. Property:
      Worst Case Complexity: O(n log(n))
      Best Case Complexity: O(n log(n))
      Average Case Complexity: O(n log(n))
      Auxiliary Space: O(n)
      Stability: No

      public int heapSplitInc(Comparable[] array, int n, int i)
      heapSplitInc. This method is likely a part of a heap-related algorithm or data structure implementation and is used to find the index of the largest child element among the left, mid, and right children of the current element at index i. The method takes an array of Comparable objects, the length of the array, and an index i as parameters.
      • The method calculates the indices of the left, mid, and right child elements of the current element index i. The left child index is (3 * i + 1), the middle child index is (3 * i + 2), and the right child index is (3 * i + 3).
      • The method then calls the heapChildInc method three times. The first call compares the current element with the left child, the second call compares the current element with the mid child, and the third call compares the current element with the right child. The heapChildInc method compares the elements at the provided indices and returns the index of the larger element.
      • The returned values from the heapChildInc method calls are assigned to the variable largest. Since each call updates largest based on the comparison result, the final value of largest represents the index of the largest child element among the left, mid, and right children.
      • Finally, the method returns the value of largest, which is the index of the largest child element among the three children of the element at index i.
      heapSplitInc method is used to find the index of the largest child element among the left, mid, and right children of a given element in a heap structure.
